{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412786"},"attributes":{"position":16,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1360"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496428"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1360"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1360"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.41,0.08,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5899"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46092"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the General Practice with a two-day history of constant right upper quadrant pain. She describes the pain as burning and always present, and denies any trauma. She has never had any pain like this before and feels generally unwell without diarrhoea or vomiting. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 124/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Chest examination is unremarkable. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the right upper quadrant with no guarding or rebound, with no obvious skin changes or bruising.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholecystitis","Herpes zoster","Acute pancreatitis","Inflammatory bowel disease","Pancreatic cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with right upper quadrant pain which could be consistent with several diagnoses. However, the burning quality of the pain and its constant nature are characteristic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eherpes zoster\u003C/strong\u003E (shingles) in its prodromal phase. Herpes zoster is caused by reactivation of latent varicella-zoster virus in the dorsal root ganglia. The pain often precedes the rash by 1-5 days (Image) and can mimic various intra-abdominal conditions when affecting thoracic or abdominal dermatomes thus must be considered as a differential for abdominal pain. Although not yet visible in this case, a unilateral, band-like distribution of vesicles along a dermatome would eventually appear and be pathognomonic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, fever, and localised tenderness. If tenderness cannot be found on gentle palpation, Murphy\u0027s sign (inspiratory arrest during palpation of the right upper quadrant) might be present. While this patient has right constant upper quadrant pain and nausea which also occurs with acute cholecystitis, the absence of guarding or rebound tenderness also makes acute cholecystitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, associated with nausea and vomiting. Laboratory findings usually include elevated lipase and amylase levels. The location of pain in the right upper quadrant rather than epigastrium makes pancreatitis less likely, though it remains in the differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E (which includes Crohn\u0027s disease and ulcerative colitis) typically presents with chronic abdominal pain, altered bowel habits, and often blood or mucus in the stool. The acute onset of symptoms and the absence of diarrhoea make irritable bowel disease an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with vague symptoms such as weight loss, abdominal pain, and jaundice. The pain is usually epigastric and radiates to the back. The acute onset of symptoms and the absence of constitutional symptoms make pancreatic cancer an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of herpes zoster includes antiviral therapy (acyclovir, valacyclovir, or famciclovir), which is most effective when started within 72 hours of rash onset. Pain management is also important, as post-herpetic neuralgia can develop, particularly in older patients. Patients should be advised that the lesions are contagious to individuals who have not had chickenpox and are not immune to varicella-zoster virus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes zoster (shingles) can present with dermatomal pain before the characteristic vesicular rash appears.","Herpes zoster affecting thoracic or abdominal dermatomes can mimic intra-abdominal pathology."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners (RACGP). Surgical Causes of Abdominal Pain [Internet]. Melbourne: The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners; 2008. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/2f869cf4-f058-4ed3-9413-ec3620c1e405/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1360"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21800"}]}}},{"t